column2:
The game is great for what it is, in fact, I've played much more than my "time on record" shows, but it's not without flaws of course.
Firstly, game crashes almost every time while doing nothing special: exiting the game, upgrading rooms, finishing a quest and going back to vault, you name it;
Secondly, rush mode is completely useless, 80% of the time it fails so you might as well just avoid it;
Sometimes weak enemies (like rad roaches) take ridiculously long time to kill and that's especially annoying when you have limited amount of healing during quests.
Aside from that, game is pretty good.

My main vault of more than 150 hours got deleted (the secondary is still there) out of the blue.

Legendary dwellers are rarer than CS:GO's rare special items, as after 76 lunchboxes opened, I got only ONE legendary dweller;

Total waste of time.

I play the game heavily on iPad, and it is neat, but I have very few pros and quite a few contras to list as to why I am not recommending this game. If you are a free to play person and don‚Äôt want to invest money into something as short-lived as Fallout Shelter, you may have to buckle up because there will be big bumps down the road. I may repeat a few things, but everything is interconnected, so bear with me, please.

Let‚Äôs begin the review!

PROS:
- free to play ‚Äì you are not forced to shell out hard-earned cash on the game in order to give it a try;

- fun, easy going, relaxing game which hilarious dwellers that say some cheesy stuff if you zoom in and read (especially flirting couples in living quarters);

- you can rename your dwellers all you like. My iPad Vault contains mash of FO and TES universes prominent characters so despite not having a legendary dweller by names of Paladin Danse and Arthur Maxson, I was able to "create" them via renaming tool and turn my Vault partly into Brotherhood of Steel HQ (given I have the themes for living quarters and diner to boot);

- quests are decent enough and early game are very captivating and addicting;

- very strong atmosphere and vibe of the main game. 



CONTRAS:
- First of all, as I have mentioned above, if you are a F2P person, buckle up for‚Ä¶ restarting you game entirely quite a few times until you hit you lucky stride right off the bet with guns/stimpacks/good legendary dwellers. I restarted my Vaults about 20 times or so until I got lucky with early lunchboxes from objectives and rolled the Vault from there. 

- Inability to connect your iPad/iPhone game to the PC;

- Small starter budget. You start with 500 caps which is nothing, especially since Rushing heavily depends on Luck SPECIAL and none of your starter dweller will have it to ensure your room rushing is successful and one has no opportunity to level up dwellers‚Äô‚Äô Luck SPECIAL early on since it takes a while before your Luck Training room becomes available;

- Every rush/dweller‚Äôs ability to find good stuff on quests and out in the Wastelands are entirely dependent on one SPECIAL trait ‚Äì Luck. The rest make no real impact on the rooms dwellers are assigned to and such. It‚Äôs stupid that Diner requires Agility as Key SPECIAL, but to rush the room, Luck plays bigger part than aforementioned Agility.  
- Complete and utter lack of weapons/stipmacks for early raiders/ghoul attacks. If early objective lunchboxes don‚Äôt drop them quickly, you are SoL and might as well restart the game anew;

- if you are an OCD builder like me, you will dislike one main thing about the game - inability to build full room, right off the bet pre-set location of elevators that one cannot move which in return off-sets the rest of the vault structure. Fully mergeable rooms are those that were built out of three blocks. However, the space you are given to work with prevents you from making every room in your vault built of three blocks to maximize the space and RSS gathering;

- inability to move your rooms/elevators around. Once you have built something the only way for you to move it is to demolish the room for skim compensation and build it elsewhere. However, you are not always able to do so due to rooms being connected to another rooms or elevators or w/e. Ergo, in some cases you are stuck with some of your building choices. 

- Vault gets attacked by raiders/ghouls/deathclaws at the most inopportune moment. Sometimes its waves after waves after waves. Good luck if you have enough weapons to arm your dwellers, otherwise you are SoL. Radscorpions will demolish your dwellers if you don‚Äôt sit and watch the whole battle tapping in timely manner to heal/rad-cure your dwellers until the monster is dead. When deathclaws attack, dwellers health drop from merely presence of the DCs. 

- Game constantly will yell at you for lack of storage. Upgrading medical bays/science labs will not increase storage capacity of the product they provide. You have to build more bays and labs to increase the cap for stimpacks and radaways. As a result, half of the vault would end up being medical facilities and warehouses.
